title: Senior Intelligence Officer
description: Chief, Transnational Issues Team, DIAC Support Division, Defense Collections Group. Oversaw the efforts of a group of collection managers to ensure the all source information needs of the analysts working Counter-terrorism, Counter-proliferation, and Counter-narcotics were met by tasking the collection systems in the Intelligence Community. Review collection to see if it was meeting the needs of the analysts and adjust accordingly. Collateral duty, Chief, Precision Collection Cell (PCC). The PCC was responsible for attacking “Hard Targets” by providing innovative all source collection strategies to meet the information needs of analysts.

title: Deputy Chief, Office of Collection Management
description: Ensured the all source information needs of DIA intelligence analysts as well as intelligence analysts supporting the Unified and Specified Commands were met by tasking the collection systems in the Intelligence Community. Review collection to see if it was meeting the needs of the analysts and adjust accordingly. When necessary, arbitrated collection operations between Warfighting Commands. Additionally, controlled the budget, administrative services, training, and personnel management. The office was mixed of 100 military and civilians. Required knowledge of each Service's and DIA's personnel rules and guidelines, DIA's and each Service's (Officer and Enlisted / Active and Reserve) personnel evaluation system as well as the DIA budget process.

title: Senior Intelligence Officer
description: DIA Liaison on future communications systems. Ensured the equities of the Defense Intelligence Agency and the intelligence components of the Joint Staff and the Unified and Specified Commands were addressed in any new communications system being planned. Collateral duties included: Directing an imagery modeling and simulations team which produce DIA's Military Assessment of Imagery Systems which evaluated the military effectiveness of future imagery collection architectures. DIA Member of the National Special Communications Working Group (NSCWG). Charter member of the NSCWG which provides special communications services in support of the Intelligence Community, Unified and Specified Commands and Operational Forces of the Services.

title: Intelligence Officer
description: One of three tasking officers responsible for reviewing and approving all requests for information entering or leaving DIA. Ensured DIA was the appropriate agency for task, that the suspense given was enough for the task being requested; reject tasks that were inappropriate for DIA to do. For accepted task, assigned to appropriate office for completion. Collateral duty: Crisis Manager, acted at Intelligence Operations Officer for various Intelligence Task Forces (ITF). Responsible for ensuring information needs of the ITF are met in a timely manner. Accept requests for information from Combatant Command being supported by the ITF. During this period I was the Operations Officer for the Iraq, Korea, Somalia, Liberia and Balkan ITFs. Additionally, I trained every Operations Officer for the ITFs for a two year period.

summary: Dynamic leader with a reputation for paradigm breaking, executing complex research, providing insightful thought provoking briefings, and fusion of all-source intelligence to meet stringent deadlines. Sets the standard for operating under pressure and coordinating geographically separated sections into a cohesive, fully capable organization. Real world expertise and mastery of a broad scope of intelligence functions (Targeting, All-Source, SIGINT, IMINT, HUMINT, OSINT, MASINT) and associated assets. Experienced and proficient in Palantir, DCGS-A, Skope Tools, ArcGIS, GoogleEarth,M3, QueryTree, Pathfinder, Harmony, HOT-R, TAC, CULTWEAVE, Clix, Chimera, Firetruck, ICREACH, Analyst Notebook and MS Office Suite. I have served eight years in the United States Army as a Military Intelligence professional. Trained as a 35F, All Source Analyst, with a specialty in targeting and Counter-Insurgency techniques. Two combat deployments to mold my intelligence process and learn functional skills. I have been honored with providing accurate and timely intelligence estimates and analysis, designing revolutionary processes for targeting, mentoring junior officers in combat scenarios for success, directly advising senior leaders, and directing multi-disciplined teams of Soldiers and Civilians through exceptionally difficult problem sets to success. title: Senior Operations Analyst
description: Provide operations advice to both SOF and conventional commanders and staff on all activities with regards to planning and synchronization of effort of JIEDDO- COIC support to deployed elements. Coordinate requests for support with other JIEDDO- COIC deployed assets as well as the JIEDDO-COIC headquarters. Ensure commanders are kept abreast of all current and emerging JIEDDO-COIC processes, methodologies, and Tactics, Techniques & Procedures (TTP) for attacking networks that employ IEDs. Provide advice to Commanders and their staff on how to best integrate JIEDDO-COIC capabilities into their ongoing operations and analytical efforts. Proficient in using the following web-based intelligence tools, software, and databases: Multimedia Message Manager (M3), Tripwire Analytic Capability (TAC), NCTC Online, Terrorism Identities Datamart Environment (TIDE), ICReach SIGINT database, Cultweave SIGINT database, PROTON SIGINT database, Skope SIGINT analytical toolkit, Analyst Notebook / Palantir link analysis software, ArcGIS spatial analysis software, Google Earth spatial analysis software, and Microsoft productivity software and applications. Also familiar with F3EAD, CALEB/IWA, Social Network Analysis and CARVER.

title: Regional Command West, Operations Lead
description: Assist in the deployment, coordination and command execution of assigned and attached units providing counter IED and direct training support advice to a combatant commander and his forces. Possess experience at tactical formations Brigade and up. Multiple combat, combat support and combat service support disciplines may be required or equivalent academic or defense industry functional areas. Develop and provide elements in identifying and addressing counter-IED capability gaps. Provide analytical tools, software development, and systems engineering support to ensure interoperability and integration of emerging counter-IED technologies and tactics, techniques and procedures. Interface with Combatant Commands, joint organizations, and OGAs on actions related to Joint IED Defeat initiatives. Provide the capability to analyze the intelligence; operational TTPs; training and materiel solution inter-relationships; and articulate an overarching strategy to combat asymmetric threats and IEDs. Observe, collect, develop, validate, and disseminate emerging IED Defeat tactics, techniques, and procedures (TTPs). Assist in identification, training, and integration of IED Defeat countermeasure technologies. Provide investigative (law enforcement)advice to unit commanders. Provide updates as required to JIEDDO OPS to ensure relevance of the JIEDDO strategy and counter-IED COP. Provide support for the execution of JIEDDO strategic actions supporting the integration of multiple Joint IED Defeat solutions throughout DoD.

title: Special Forces (Ret)
description: 18E - Senior Communications Expert Perform setup, configuration, operation, and maintenance of satellite communications network and global positioning equipment, integration of RF over fiber optic cabling; the effectiveness of critical agency assets. Preparing and briefing senior leaders of system capabilities and limitations and provide guidance and assistance in implementation of policy and procedures as it relates to daily operation, projects, and Continuity of Operations (COOP) plans. Planning, evaluating, selecting, and procuring necessary RF and encryption equipment or services to support the organization’s continuity of operations mission. Providing guidance on RF network security to include configurations, establishment of standard operating procedures (SOPs), and input on design analysis and support for the review of existing and future multi-node ground stations and operational system. The RF systems will integrate with the enterprise architecture necessary to assure the successful operation of an integrated GSA network capability supporting internal and external customers 18F - Intel Sergeant Employs conventional and unconventional warfare tactics and techniques in intelligence collection and processing. Provides tactical and technical guidance to the Detachment Commander, indigenous and allied personnel. Plans, organizes, trains, advises, assists and supervises indigenous and allied personnel on collection and processing of intelligence information. Performs intelligence and operational duties when task organized in preparation (isolation) for special missions and during operations. 18Z - Senior Enlisted Advisor Supervises, instructs and serves as the senior enlisted member for SF activities. Trains and maintains proficiency in all major duties associated with Special Forces. Performs joint, interagency, multi-national, combined, and coalition planning

summary: Proven leader with a highly successful career in managing targeting and intelligence operations. This career began with providing Signals Intelligence (SIGINT) support, and Arabic to English translations, for multiple forward deployed US Special Forces Operational Detachment Alphas (ODA) in Northern Africa (OEF-TS), Non-Commissioned Officer In Charge (NCOIC) of Signals Terminal Guidance and Tactical Site Exploitation for a Multi Function Team in support of Operation Iraqi Freedom and culminated with providing SIGINT advice and guidance to national level intelligence agencies. Over a 6-year distinguished military career demonstrated progressive decision making and leadership of both SIGINT intelligence analysts as well as All-source and Human Intelligence (HUMINT) personnel in support of targeting/attacking insurgent networks. As a government contractor, served as the Counter IED (CIED) SIGINT team leader in support of two Army Infantry Brigades operating in the Afghanistan Theater of Operations (ATO). Identified, developed, tracked and provided detailed SIGINT analysis in support of neutralizing Insurgent and IED networks. This unique blend of tactical and strategic experience has created an invaluable skill-set in problem solving in diverse areas, including: strategic planning & communications; policy analysis and developing interoperability between international/interagency organizations with a common goal of intelligence fusion in support of targeting enemy networks. Strengths include: extensive experience in positions of leadership, training, leading and adapting teams to meet specific requirements for national policy makers; a tested, proactive, participative management style; excellent communications and presentation skills; exceptional analytical abilities; proven ability to succeed in high risk & challenging environments while displaying the highest standards of professional excellence and personal integrity.Specialties:Modern Standard Arabic, Signals Intelligence Analysis; NSAnet databases; Association, Mainway, SIGNAV, Cultweave, SEDB, RTRG, Octave and Globalreach, USSIDS governing SIGINT exploitation and dissemination, Analyst Notebook and ArcGIS/Google Earth, Microsoft Office; Powerpoint, Word, Excel, mIRC and Jabber Chat, GSM Theory and VHF/UHF, technical knowledge of Signals Terminal Guidance Equipment; Stingray, Kingfish, Growler and HEAT, Oneroof/Digital Receiver Technology (DRT), PRD- 13.

title: Analyst Consultant
description: • Guided and instructed customers in processing data to ensure the best quality of analysis was obtained. • Delivered distinctive (unprecedented) case successes, and countless standard (improvement) case successes, mixed with dozens of positive remarks on provided services, executive-level demonstrations of impact of this project; all of which aiding in the establishment of a 5 year contract extension worth $5mil/yr. • Encouraged a measurably improved shift in the limited collaborative practices of a challenging federal law enforcement agency, by providing leadership and customer-oriented consulting services centered on empathy, analytical discovery, and demonstrable success. • Ensured processed data was normalized and derived from a reliable source thus producing high quality products. These products were then presented to key decision makers allowing from them to make the most informed decisions regarding pattern of life (PoL) analysis of counter narcotics (CN), counter proliferation (CP), threat finance, anti-money laundering (AML) and immigration fraud cases. • Experienced in predictive and behavioral analytics associated with big data. • Developed SOP’s for tactical and strategic level analyst associated with AML Suspicious Activity Reports (SAR), CP, CN, and PoL. • Lead a team of 5 providing guidance and SME support. Additionally devised and performed the first company climate assessment. • Coordinated a $20k/month account with 100% accuracy, managing the distribution of manpower of an 18 man team on a geographically dispersed project. • Provided users with tactical and strategic level support by helping them integrate HUMINT, GEOINT, temporal analysis, and social media. Primary POC for analysis of illegal financial based transactions and counter narcotics activities with a focus on the SW and NE borders.

title: All Source Network Analyst
description: • Developed a Palantir based ontology and methodology allowing for the Critical Factors Analysis (CFA) mission to integrate with all other mission in JIEDDO. • Performed SWOT analysis on insurgent networks so that decision makers were aware of the strategic state of the battle field. • Instructed and facilitated a team of 10 people, training them to integrate the strategic methodology of CFA with the database of Palantir to further the customer base of CFA in support of missions within JIEDDO. • Guided an 8 person team enabling the production of intelligence assessments on adversarial networks in support of lethal and non-lethal counter-IED network operations and counter narcotics in the Afghanistan theaters of operation. • Team SME on activity in the RC-SW and coordinated with Afghan, Iraq, and MENA teams • Communicated with 2nd party nation representatives regularly in support of current activities in the battle space. • Ensured that all data that was being processed by the team was derived from a quality source and that all products pushed out from the team was of a high integrity. • Responsible for producing SITREPS that were then provided directly to the units’ deployed downrange regarding enemy IED Tactics, Techniques, and Procedures (TTP). • Supported the development of a knowledge base utilizing Palantir software program for use by the War Fighters by fusing mutli-core intelligence reports such as; biometric data, weapons intelligence data, document and media exploitation data, SIGINT, GEOINT, and HUMINT. • Team briefer for Executive Intelligence Officers on mission capabilities. • Built HVI target packages, fusing of tactical, theater and national level intelligence, and working within the inter-agency, coalition and joint service environments supporting combat operations.

title: NTI Intelligence Analyst
description: • Responsible for briefing Senior Intelligence Officers on a daily basis, and increase the situational awareness for national and tactical customers. • Provided direct support to the Combined Force Air Component Commander, Air Force Cryptologic Service Group, and forward deployed units with information ascertained through C4ISR systems.. • Provided guidance and leadership to 5 people in order to help them further their careers and develop their skills. • Responsible for conducting performance evaluations and handling confrontational situations among the troops as well as issuing reprimand statements. • Provided mission exploitation support against Mid East adversaries by use of language and cultural expertise. • Reported to the Director of Operations and Unit Commander on the status of Operations Training of C4ISR systems. • Maintained and managed the training process and programs of a 200+ man unit and revolutionized the personnel training record program. • Provided management with newly developed training material to guide their personnel’s initial qualification and upgrade training for multiple SIGINT and IMINT based missions.

title: Intelligence Analyst
description: Supports F3EAD ops. Uses data from all sources to make predictive assessments, answer RFIs, and provide intelligence to SOF customers. Key Contributions/Tasks: • Uses all-source intelligence data, answers RFI from deployed SOF, fills current/identifies new intelligence gaps, prepares operational risk assessments, writes operational summaries, and builds target packets, supporting SOF combat operations • Performs high level analysis using Geospatial Information Systems (GIS) applications, fuses disparate SIGINT derived traffic data, raw COMINT, HUMINT reporting, and GEOINT data, creates VEO network link-analysis charts, makes predictive threat assessments, identifies common contacts, critical communications nodes, HVT locations/PoL, and targetable opportunities; feeds F3EAD target cycle • Regularly performs Processing Exploitation and Dissemination (PED) of Hyper-spectral imagery (HSI), multi-spectral imagery (MSI), Panchromatic imagery (PAN), Synthetic Aperture Radar (SAR), Infrared (IR), Light Detection and Ranging (LiDAR), elevation data, and Full-Motion Video (FMV), creates detailed customer tailored fused GEOINT products, supporting intelligence preparation of the battle-space (IPB), supporting lethal and non-lethal F3EAD operations • Regularly leads teams of five in high stress environments, consistently and accurately relays EEI information, manages production requirements, acts as 11IS SOF PED liaison to ITC and flight crew, ensures timely support for F3EAD operations • Compares COMINT with near-real-time FMV observations, supports temporal-spatial correlation of HVT • Lead analyst, attends high level unit planning meetings, worked with other leads to identify areas for improvement, develop new training tools, and share successful new techniques • Leads two counter terrorism focused all-source collaboration teams, leverages team-members experiences to collaborate, make accurate analytic assessments, and disseminate intelligence products to deployed units

title: ISR Tactical Controller (ITC)
description: Supported SOF targeting and strike operations. Responsible for the coordination and tasking of manned and unmanned ISR asset collections and the fusion of other source and HUMINT derived intelligence to develop POL of HVTs and aid the creation of HVT target packages for strike forces. Provided force protection over-watch through ISR assets during live assault operations and radio operator responsible for passing key information to and from the ground assault forces and the operations commander. Key Contributions/Tasks: Directed and dynamically tasked up to six ISR assets while supporting two major combat operations targeting national level ISI leadership and extortion ring leaders. Resulted in major disruption of ISI terrorist network and led to actionable intelligence targeting top two HVI in Iraq. Received TF coin and letter of commendation Developed integrated collections plans employing ISR assets to collect IMINT, COMINT, and SIGINT data to develop NAI, establish POL, corroborate HUMINT reporting, populate GEOINT databases and meet triggers for over 30 top HVI, directed 1000+ hours of collection, supported all levels of the SOF F3EAD targeting cycle

title: Theater Collections manager
description: Served as part of a theater collections hub for PACOM (Jan07-Nov07). Monitored and reviewed raw (voice) and digital communications; filed and authored daily reports. Provide Signal Security (SIGSEC) assessments during USSOCOM execution of sensitive Secretary of Defense (SECDEF) and Joint Chiefs of Staff (JCS) directed exercises. Produced daily tactical intelligence reports highlighting vulnerabilities meeting commanders’ priority intelligence requirements (PIR). Used signals intelligence (SIGINT) tools and databases to develop pattern of life (POL) analysis, such as IC Reach, FIRETRUCK, Cultweave, SKOPE Tools, Association, and cellular exploitation (CELLEX) techniques; constructed call-chain diagrams in Analyst’s Notebook for social networking analysis (SNA). Used various communications networks and programs, such as NSA Net, JWICS, SIPRnet, the JSOC Information Automated Network (JIANT), the Special Operations Intelligence System (SOIS), and military internet relay char (mIRC), for information sharing and coordination.

title: All Source Intelligence Analyst/ 35F
description: CI/HUMINT Targeting Officer/All Source Analyst, U.S Central Command (Tampa & Orlando, FL), Oct 09 – Oct 12 • Supported deployed combat forces with operational targeting and lead development meeting priority and national level HUMINT requirement standards which required specialized DIA training and certification • Assigned to U.S. CENTCOM’s Trans Regional Energy Infrastructure Team, responsible for researching, analyzing, authoring, and coordinating products highlighting the effect of international oil and gas markets on CENTCOM’s area of responsibility • Conducted thorough investigations utilizing specialized commercial, internet, and proprietary databases to monitor and assess developments associated with the Middle East energy and water supplies and how they influence maritime oil markets, economies, government relations, terrorist threats, and response plans • Coordinated with Combatant Command’s and other national level intelligence entities to provide intelligence recommendations All Source Intelligence Analyst, 143d Expeditionary Sustainment Command (Kandahar, Afghanistan), Feb 08 – Oct 09 • Deployed to Afghanistan in support of Operation Enduring Freedom (OEF) with the 143d Expeditionary Sustainment Brigade, providing all source analysis to the first Expeditionary Sustainment Command to enter Afghanistan • Responsible for written intelligence products and briefings advising 143rd Command leadership regarding threats to air, land, and sea assets for the sustainment of combat operations • Established, coordinated, and maintained intelligence liaison relationships with coalition partners positioned throughout Afghanistan founding the first monthly Joint Intelligence Team in Kandahar’s Intelligence Fusion Center including five North Atlantic Treaty Organization (NATO) countries that support tactical logistics operations • Created and authored 280 Joint Sustainment Command Intelligence Summaries, which were the Command’s primary intelligence reference

Assures intelligence producers plans and operations align with current and future strategic intelligence objectives •Employs the following methods to interact with Iraqi officials: continuous personal contact to establish mutual trust, confidence and confidentiality; presentation of substantive material on general and specific subjects related to the mission; assistance on the development, implementation and oversight of policies and procedures that enable them to fulfill their intelligence mission (Communication Security, Information Security, and Physical Security) •Supports Deputy Commanding General Advisory and Training Mission Iraq and Develops Iraqi security forces and ministries, by delivering SIGINT training and equipment fielding for the Iraqi Ministry of Defense •Coordinates with Intelligence Military Security School (IMSS) staff in developing Intelligence training for the Iraqi National intelligence Community •Mobile Team Trainer (MTT) for 13 Iraqi Army Intelligence Surveillance and Reconnaissance (ISR) Divisions in signals of interest collection Tactics, Techniques, and Procedures (TTP) •Supported MULTI-NATIONAL SECURITY TRANSITION COMMAND IRAQ (MNSTC-I) Baghdad, Iraq

title: Insurgent Network / Identity Exploitation / Intelligence Analyst
description: • Experience working in a 24x7x365 Security Operations Center (SOC)& Sensitive Compartmented Information Facilities (SCIF) • Familiarity with Intelligence Organizations, Disciplines, Systems, Analysis, Security, Processes • Responsible for Exploiting, analyzing, researching, reporting, database management and dissemination C-IED/RCIED mission analysis briefings and annexes, High Value Individual targeting products, Mobile C4 Networks, THREAT NETWORK model analysis, Insurgent IED cell activities, Analyzing links and nodes, and All-Source exploitation of documents and media from C- IED operations and detainees. • Responsible for Intercept, Identify, Classify and determine the source and location of hostile Communications and Radio Signals • Knowledgeable in SIGINT, COMINT, ELINT, GEOINT, MASINT, IMINT, HUMINT, •Counterintelligence, All-Source Analyst, Counterterrorism, Physical Security •Familiarity with Army intelligence systems/platforms that the TCC interacts with: JCATS, CIDNE, DCGS, DCGS-A, JSTARS, IWS, TES, DTES, GRCS, PROPHET, etc. • SIGINT capabilities include the collection and exploitation of communication signals and interception of electromagnetic signals, such as radar and weapons systems, for Electronic Intelligence (EI). • Performed SIGINT/COMINT Target Development for analysis of sea, air, and ground platforms • Experienced with Guardrail Common Sensor (GRCS), Communication High Accuracy Airborne Location System (CHAALS), and Advanced QUICK LOOK (AQL) •Familiarity Find, Fix, Finish, Exploit, Analyze and Disseminate (F3EAD) battle command process. • Knowledge of Foreign Satellite Interception (FORNSAT), Radio Frequency (RF), and SCS systems capabilities •Provided support to the ISR (Intelligence, Surveillance, and Reconnaissance) synchronization process • Knowledge of Satellite communication (SATCOM) communications and systems • Knowledgeable of Defense & Space four Orbit regimes •Familiarity (F3EAD) battle command process.

title: Intelligence SME (Principal)
company: NEK Advanced Securities Group, Inc./ Blue Light Services
description: Nov 2012 – Oct 2014: Senior All- Source Intelligence SME, Counter-Improvised Explosive Device Operations Integrations Center (COIC), Joint Improvised Explosive Device Defeat Organization (JIEDDO), Blue Light Services (formerly NEK), Reston, VA • Deployed to Helmand Province, Afghanistan and provided direct all source analytical support to TF Helmand (Herrick 19, UK). Directly supervised four subordinate analysts and led analytical efforts in support of the customer. Recognized by the commander of TF Helmand for outstanding support. Provided liaison link with neighboring SOF forces to provide the customer with situational awareness of SOF operations that were directly influencing their battle space. • Developed, coordinated, facilitated, and performed multi-intelligence analysis and fusion in support of CIED efforts and operations integrating national level products and databases to provide an enhanced level of CIED information support. • Conducted link chart analysis utilizing ANB to develop insurgent networks. • Responded to client's RFIs utilizing Pathfinder, M.E.T.R.I.C.S., Cultweave, QueryTree, Palantir, ODLAW, Analyst Notebook (ANB), WebTAS, HOTR, GETS, and CIDNE. Developed all source analytical product utilizing ArcGIS and GoogleEarth to geospatially depict information. • Provided intelligence and forensic expertise and support with respect to munitions exploitation (Weapons Technical Intelligence). • Conducted asymmetric threat analysis and exploitation. • Identified intelligence gaps, specified and submitted collection requirements to collection manager and analysts. • Identified significant intelligence trends and proposed new or revised analytical efforts to alert leadership to developments and meet customer needs. Analysis focused on network structures, operational capabilities, technologies, and support to CIED targeting operations. • Conducted social network analysis to identify vulnerabilities within adversary organizations that may be exploited.

title: Intelligence Sergeant Major
description: Led a multi-discipline intelligence organization in joint intelligence operations in support of operations in Regional Command-East, Afghanistan in support of NATO/ISAF objectives. Vetted contract intelligence analyst hires and assignments within RC-E area of operations. Coordinated with Program Managers to support contract intelligence analysts at COPs and FOBs. Coordinated intelligence objectives of RC-E with NATO/ISAF CJ2. Conducted battlefield circulation to forward COPs and FOBs to facilitate intelligence activities of contract and military intelligence analysts. Successfully negotiated with Senior leadership, including General Officers, to reorganize of the RC-E CJ2 Intelligence Enterprise to eliminate duplication of effort and streamline intelligence production.

title: S2 NCOIC/Detachment Sergeant
description:  Served as the Senior Intelligence Noncommissioned Officer for the 10th Special Forces Group (Airborne); responsible for planning and advising intelligence manning, resourcing, and training for the Special Forces Group; responsible for supporting USEUCOM, USCENTCOM, SOCCENT, and SOCEUR missions as directed, to include Operation IRAQI FREEDOM; managed 1 million dollar Group Intelligence training budget; developed and implemented a comprehensive training program for newly assigned all-source intelligence analysts that became the model for the entire unit, and served as the basis for the planned special operations training and assessment course; supervised the fielding of garrison DCGS-A suites and subsequent analyst training plan; directly responsible for supervision, training, and professional development for eight military personnel and one DoD Civilian.  Deployed in support of Operation IRAQI FREEDOM II, III, IV, and V; served in positions of increasing responsibility beginning with All-Source Production Section NCOIC and culminating as the J2 Senior Enlisted Advisor for the Combined Joint Special Operations Task Force-Arabian Peninsula managing the production and fusion of multi-discipline intelligence products for a 112 person joint intelligence directorate supporting all special operations forces in Iraq; managed a multi-million dollar SCIF renovation project including all work orders, life support, security, and automation upgrades; managed the fielding of a deployed DCGS-A server suite and BAL lifecycle replacement; developed WebTAS and CIDNE training plans for all intelligence personnel; responsible for training, evaluations, and awards for 112 Soldiers, Sailors, Airmen, Marines, DoD Civilians, and contractors in a Combined-Joint Special Operations environment, produced and provided quality control for reports and briefings produced for field grade and general officers, SES-level personnel, and other governmental agencies.

title: Intel Observer/Controller
description:  Responsible for coordinating and fusing all data collection from tactical analysis into formal Intelligence multimedia After Action Reviews for Brigade, Battalion, Company, and Platoon level presentations; supervised, trained, and led six DoD civilian personnel; developed Intelligence Observer/Controller training plan and smart book for newly assigned Intelligence Officers and NCOs, and individual augmentees; trained over 300 Soldiers on all facets of tactical intelligence in support of full spectrum operations, Operation ENDURING FREEDOM, KFOR, and SFOR.  Additional duties included serving as Information Assurance Manager responsible for 44 computer systems; responsible for life cycle replacement, accreditation packets, annual command inspections, new user training and account set-up, division webmaster, and first line system troubleshooting and maintenance.

title: Intelligence Analyst/Targeting Sergeant
description: Deployed to Afghanistan with 3rd Special Forces Group as the Joint Intelligence Operations Officer (2006) and to Iraq as the Senior Targeting Analyst (2008). title: Maritime Security Specialist/Team Leader Corporal/E4
description: Deployed with 1st Marine Division as a Mortarman Team Leader, assigned to a Marine amphibious assault force, using combat rubber reconnaissance craft (CRRC). After deployment, was selected to be a part of the Maritime Special Purpose Force (MSPF) Platoon for 1st Marine Division. This platoon is a unique specialized sub-unit trained in hostage rescue, urban warfare, and was tasked as a TRAP (Tactical Recovery of Aircraft and Pilot) platoon when deployed overseas. • Trained in Close Quarters Battle (CQB), Explosive Breaching, Applied Military Demolition, and Containment Security in support of Maritime Special Purpose Force (MSPF) operations • Conducted training with joint military Special Operation forces and federal/local law enforcement agencies to ensure training remained current and relative • In charge of a 4-man infantry team. Responsible for the health, well-being, and performance of a fire team unit • Trained and supervised mortar team members in the tactical employment of 60 mm mortar as part of a Marine amphibious assault force, using combat rubber reconnaissance craft (CRRC) • Trained for and conducted OCONUS clandestine amphibious operations while assigned to 1st Marine Division while deployed to multiple countries

title: Lead Intelligence Analyst
description: Deployed to Afghanistan serving as the Operations LNO and Lead All-Source Analyst for in RC-North. Prepared briefings for Army Major Commands in Afghanistan with emphasis on the use of IEDs by threat groups. As part of the intelligence cycle, conducted all-source intelligence research using databases and developed intelligence capability and threat assessments using intelligence information systems. Served as Senior All-Source Analyst for the Iraq MND Center/South Team preparing daily briefings for the MID Chief. Provided Human Intelligence (HUMINT) and All-Source Analysis support to combat units through research and dissemination of products on asymmetric threats, with emphasis on the use of IEDs by threat groups. Identified emerging trends and methods of operation in order to deter and interdict networks associated with the sourcing, production, delivery and emplacement of IEDs. Analyzed in-theater data to strengthen information gathering capabilities through fusion analysis. Planned, coordinated and synthesized research to produce all-source intelligence products through fusion analysis combining HUMINT, Signals Intelligence (SIGINT), IMINT, Open Source Intelligence (OSINT) and ISR Optimization to answer Requests for Support (RFS) at all levels.

title: Counterterrorism Analyst
description: Performed in depth all-source analysis on subjects of counterterrorism interest in order to provide actionable intelligence in support of the FBI operational divisions, headquarters counterterrorism elements, field offices and Joint Terrorism Task Forces. Leveraged all-source intelligence research, exploitation and analytical methods as well as electronic, manual, and automatic databases to identify, validate, and or supplement current information on persons of investigative interest and interfaced with local and national clients and or agencies of the intelligence community as well as Major Commands. Liaised with case field agents and other analysts to establish analytical requirements and provide products. Produced information papers and finished analytical products for dissemination to a variety of Task Force consumers, often including visual representations such as link analysis. Provided technical guidance mentoring to colleagues and junior analysts regarding analytical methods and capabilities. Responded to requests for intelligence and background information from various customers.

title: All Source Intelligence Analyst
description: Supervised and managed three junior intelligence analysts of the intelligence section responsible for supporting U.S. Army Special Operations Forces (SOF) teams as well as Army Major Commands in the Iraq and Afghanistan Regions. Developed military intelligence fusion products on foreign ground forces techniques, tactics, and procedures, and provided intelligence to deployed U.S. Forces, force developers, and decision makers at both the national and worldwide levels. Monitored both domestic and international reporting to provide tactical, strategic and operational support to Special Forces Teams; this included producing daily intelligence and warning reports on imminent and emerging threats to Special Forces Teams operating outside of the US. Prepared and coordinated strategic and operational level all-source reports, presentations, and briefings with supporting documentation produced by members of the intelligence community. Wrote information papers and intelligence articles for SOF units. Manipulated intelligence data and delivered capability briefings. Researched electronic, manual, and automatic databases. Developed intelligence capability and threat assessments using intelligence information systems. Utilized intelligence analysis tools and databases such as ASAL-L, RWS, Falcon view, Analyst Notebook, Pathfinder, C2PC2, ArcGIS, Starlight and AMHS to produce timely and accurate reporting to operational elements.

title: Senior Operations Analyst
description: Provide operations advice to both SOF and conventional commanders and staff on all activities with regards to planning and synchronization of effort of JIEDDO- COIC support to deployed elements. Also familiar with F3EAD, CALEB/IWA, Social Network Analysis and CARVER.

title: Regional Command West, Operations Lead
description: Assist in the deployment, coordination and command execution of assigned and attached units providing counter IED and direct training support advice to a combatant commander and his forces. Possess experience at tactical formations Brigade and up. Multiple combat, combat support and combat service support disciplines may be required or equivalent academic or defense industry functional areas. Develop and provide elements in identifying and addressing counter-IED capability gaps. Provide analytical tools, software development, and systems engineering support to ensure interoperability and integration of emerging counter-IED technologies and tactics, techniques and procedures. Interface with Combatant Commands, joint organizations, and OGAs on actions related to Joint IED Defeat initiatives. Provide the capability to analyze the intelligence; operational TTPs; training and materiel solution inter-relationships; and articulate an overarching strategy to combat asymmetric threats and IEDs. Observe, collect, develop, validate, and disseminate emerging IED Defeat tactics, techniques, and procedures (TTPs). Assist in identification, training, and integration of IED Defeat countermeasure technologies. Provide investigative (law enforcement)advice to unit commanders. Provide updates as required to JIEDDO OPS to ensure relevance of the JIEDDO strategy and counter-IED COP. Provide support for the execution of JIEDDO strategic actions supporting the integration of multiple Joint IED Defeat solutions throughout DoD.

title: Special Forces (Ret)
description: 18E - Senior Communications Expert Perform setup, configuration, operation, and maintenance of satellite communications network and global positioning equipment, integration of RF over fiber optic cabling; the effectiveness of critical agency assets. Preparing and briefing senior leaders of system capabilities and limitations and provide guidance and assistance in implementation of policy and procedures as it relates to daily operation, projects, and Continuity of Operations (COOP) plans. Planning, evaluating, selecting, and procuring necessary RF and encryption equipment or services to support the organization’s continuity of operations mission. Providing guidance on RF network security to include configurations, establishment of standard operating procedures (SOPs), and input on design analysis and support for the review of existing and future multi-node ground stations and operational system. The RF systems will integrate with the enterprise architecture necessary to assure the successful operation of an integrated GSA network capability supporting internal and external customers 18F - Intel Sergeant Employs conventional and unconventional warfare tactics and techniques in intelligence collection and processing. Provides tactical and technical guidance to the Detachment Commander, indigenous and allied personnel. Plans, organizes, trains, advises, assists and supervises indigenous and allied personnel on collection and processing of intelligence information. Performs intelligence and operational duties when task organized in preparation (isolation) for special missions and during operations. 18Z - Senior Enlisted Advisor Supervises, instructs and serves as the senior enlisted member for SF activities. Trains and maintains proficiency in all major duties associated with Special Forces. Performs joint, interagency, multi-national, combined, and coalition planning

company: US Army HQS Intelligence and Security Command (INSCOM)

summary: I see myself as a teacher and mentor acting as a guide for students on a wonderful journey discovering the English language in writing and reading. I take my students beyond the tourist hot spots and into the hole-in-the-wall cafes, street markets, and sometimes unsafe neighborhoods, where they develop more than just grammar, spelling, punctuation, and required writing skills, but acquire a love of language. From time to time, I do take temporary jobs, such as my current position as an analyst and reporter. Specialties: Speculative Fiction, Horror, Poetry

summary: I see myself as a teacher and mentor acting as a guide for students on a wonderful journey discovering the English language in writing and reading. I take my students beyond the tourist hot spots and into the hole-in-the-wall cafes, street markets, and sometimes unsafe neighborhoods, where they develop more than just grammar, spelling, punctuation, and required writing skills, but acquire a love of language. From time to time, I do take temporary jobs, such as my current position as an analyst and reporter. Specialties: Speculative Fiction, Horror, Poetry

title: Sr All Source Intelligence Analyst
description: -Serving as a Principal All Source Intelligence Analyst for IJC, Kabul, AFG. -Provide IJC J2 Theater Wide Intelligence products and analysis identifying and defeating Networks utilizing IEDs and other means targeting US and Coalition Forces operating in Afghanistan. -Provide multi-intelligence analysis and fusion in support of Counter-IED efforts and operations executed by committed war fighting units, integrating existing National-level products and databases to provide an enhanced level of information support.- - Conduct multi-layered, multi-intelligence analysis to define patterns of IED network activity. - Provide intelligence targeting support products and "reach-back" support to forward-deployed elements as required. - Provide classified/unclassified briefings to customers and senior decision makers. - Conduct adversary analysis to assist all COIC and JIEDDO divisions and selected key external agencies in achieving predicative counter-IED capabilities. - Utilize Link Analysis, GMTI, Imagery, and other All-Source analysis to develop products in support of MASINT-enabled Dynamic products for Planning and Targeting by both special operations and conventional forces against insurgent networks.

summary: Retired U.S. Marine Nov 1990- Nov 2010 offering over 24 years of leadership experience in training, management, and operational expertise combining military (0211/3051/8511) along with civilian deployment experience. Years of proven success in a wide variety of circumstances and under stressful and complex situations including ground combat operations and deployments overseas locations, to include ship deployment. Completes complicated tasks and solves problems as part of a team or as independent operator. Sr Intelligence All Source Analyst in regards to Tactical, Operational, and Strategic level experience: C-IED Attack the Network & Defeat the Device Concept, Asymmetric, Counter Insurgency, full spectrum and stability post conflict/disaster operations including: 13th MEU 2000-1, EOC Seoul Korea 2004-06, OEF Iraq Jan 2003, 2007, 08, and 2009, and OIF Afghanistan Dec 2010, 2011, 2012-2013, and 2014 Jan-?. Specialties Skilled as Sr. Contract Lead Analyst: 14 years Counterintelligence/Force Protection. Team Lead, Trainer, and Mentor. 4+ years Counter-IED SR SME. Specializing in working for and solving Defense and Military related industry problems and tasks.Recommend, contribute, and advise Sr Leaders and customers for Counter IED Work Groups. Enjoy working in CONUS and OCONUS assignments. Proficient with: COIC Tool suites (NUDOP, DARC Raids, and RAT TOOL) ARCGIS 10.0, MS Office Suite 2007(advanced Excel), Palantir, Catapult Search, Quiver, CellPack, CIDNE/WEBTAS, TIGR, DCGS-A, Google Earth (Advanced CENTRIX, SIPR, & TLAN), M3, Geobrowser, and many other operations and intelligence tools. Advanced Training on: Palantir , Analyst Notebook, Vizio, TAC, HOT-R, Terra Explorer, SIGINT based tools, and AXIS-PRO.

title: Principal All Source Intelligence Lead Analyst
description: - Served as a Training SME for the JCAST/COIC Training Division conducting awareness, capabilities, and unit training and familiarization of tool capabilities to current and future customers. -Create, assist, recommend, and implement "Best Practices" capabilities to enhance future training and course curriculum for commanders and the warfighter. - Served as the Sr Contract Lead Analyst for the COIC in Bagram RC-East (2012-13) with 1ID and 101st. - Previously deployed to Helmand Province (2010) and COIC-A in Bagram (2011) in Afghanistan asa All Source Analyst (SME) with RCT 8 2/1 Marines - Responsible for coordinating, assigning, and oversight for team intelligence products. - Provide exploitation and asymmetric threat analysis including the identification, development, and integration of countermeasure technologies. -Served as advisor to the Commanding General on the weekly Counter IED Work Group - Provide multi-intelligence analysis and fusion in support of Counter-IED efforts and operations executed by committed war fighting units, integrating existing national-level products and databases to provide an enhanced level of information support.- - Conduct multi-layered, multi-intelligence analysis to define patterns of IED network activity in order to narrow the search space to conduct CIED operations. - Provide intelligence targeting support products and "reach-back" support to forward-deployed elements as required. - Conduct adversary analysis to assist all COIC and JIEDDO divisions and selected key external agencies in achieving predicative counter-IED capabilities. - Utilize Link Analysis, GMTI, Imagery, and other All-Source analysis to develop products in support of MASINT-enabled Dynamic products for Planning and Targeting by both special operations and conventional forces against HME and insurgent networks.

summary: Retired U.S. Marine Nov 1990- Nov 2010 offering over 24 years of leadership experience in training, management, and operational expertise combining military (0211/3051/8511) along with civilian deployment experience. Years of proven success in a wide variety of circumstances and under stressful and complex situations including ground combat operations and deployments overseas locations, to include ship deployment. Completes complicated tasks and solves problems as part of a team or as independent operator. Sr Intelligence All Source Analyst in regards to Tactical, Operational, and Strategic level experience: C-IED Attack the Network & Defeat the Device Concept, Asymmetric, Counter Insurgency, full spectrum and stability post conflict/disaster operations including: 13th MEU 2000-1, EOC Seoul Korea 2004-06, OEF Iraq Jan 2003, 2007, 08, and 2009, and OIF Afghanistan Dec 2010, 2011, 2012-2013, and 2014 Jan-?. Specialties Skilled as Sr. Contract Lead Analyst: 14 years Counterintelligence/Force Protection. Team Lead, Trainer, and Mentor. 4+ years Counter-IED SR SME. Specializing in working for and solving Defense and Military related industry problems and tasks.Recommend, contribute, and advise Sr Leaders and customers for Counter IED Work Groups. Enjoy working in CONUS and OCONUS assignments. Proficient with: COIC Tool suites (NUDOP, DARC Raids, and RAT TOOL) ARCGIS 10.0, MS Office Suite 2007(advanced Excel), Palantir, Catapult Search, Quiver, CellPack, CIDNE/WEBTAS, TIGR, DCGS-A, Google Earth (Advanced CENTRIX, SIPR, & TLAN), M3, Geobrowser, and many other operations and intelligence tools. Advanced Training on: Palantir , Analyst Notebook, Vizio, TAC, HOT-R, Terra Explorer, SIGINT based tools, and AXIS-PRO.

title: Intelligence Analyst
description: • Processed all source information and generated source directed requirements (SDRs) and collection plans in support of US Forces Korea. • Produced source validation and operational recommendations for five HUMINT Collection Teams during OIF. • Primary S2X representative to Brigade targeting meetings, briefing senior personnel on HUMINT capabilities and assessments of feasibility for future targeting operations. • Conducted social network analysis (SNA), open source data mining, and helped design spotting procedures for Special Operations Command Africa (SOCAFRICA). • Contributed to 300% increase in operations by planning and validating ISR strategy for Combined Special Operations Task Force-10 (CSOTF-10) during Operation Enduring Freedom (OEF). • Dynamically tasked and guided airborne IMINT/SIGINT assets for CSOTF-10 ground teams during OEF. • Researched, reviewed, edited and disseminated all-source theater intelligence briefs on foreign military capabilities and leadership for US Africa Command (AFRICOM) AOR. • Team Leader for analysts providing daily Order of Battle updates to United States Army Africa (USARAF) during Operation Unified Protector for use in targeting operations. • Member of theater level G2 staff planning during Arab Spring uprisings. • Proficient with multiple tools and web applications to include: Palantir, Analyst Notebook, CIDNE, ICReach, Cultweave, Swordfish-J, Biometric Automated Toolset (BATS), Terrorist Identities Datamart Enterprise (TIDE), SharePoint portals, HOT-R, Coliseum, M3, Harmony, ArcGIS, Google Earth. • One of two US partners on an OEF NATO operations floor, mentoring on the usage of ISR assets. • Developed exemplars and processes for improving HUMINT and Analytical Control Element (ACE) operations. • Constantly took lead on intelligence operations, excelling at organizing the team into its most efficient and effective model.

description: Core Technologies: INTELINK, SIPRNET, NIPRNET, ArcView, ArcGIS, Webtas, DCGS-A, Google Earth, TIGR, mIRC, JCHAT, Track 24, Blue Force Tracker, CPOF Supervise and mentor five-member team of analysts; interface with Area Office Officers and Security Liaison Teams (SLTs) to support reconstruction and defense efforts. Review and edit all reports prior to dissemination.

title: ISR Collection Manager
description: Functioned as a part of an intelligence analytical team of military and/or DoD civilian analysts in support of USFORA,CJTF Paladin, Regional Command, BCT/RCT/MEU/MEB/Coalition Brigade CJ2 staffs' analytical requirements. Responsible for coordinating all C-IED (Counter-Improvised Explosive Device) ISR collection requirements and ensured all intelligence data was properly disseminated within the supported command/organization. Developed, maintained and updated collection plans based on the supported Commander's Priority Intelligence Requirements prioritized in support of C-IED specific targets. Monitored a wide range of available organic and nonorganic collection systems for newly nominated requirements, then validated and distributed them, as required. Prepared ISR assessment metrics of IMINT, SIGINT, HUMINT, and MASINT products to gauge the effectiveness of collection operations. Interfaced with higher, lateral and subordinate commands/organizations' Collection and Requirements Managers including entities within ANSF/GIRoA to answer intelligence related RFIs and deconflict or collaborate on AOR C-IED requirements and reporting.

title: Human Intelligence (HUMINT) Analysis Cell (HAC) Team Lead
description: Served as an Intelligence Analyst supporting the Human Intelligence (HUMINT) Analysis Cell (HAC) for the 3-2nd Brigade Combat team (BCT) S-2, and previously for the 116th BCT S-2, in Afghanistan. Conducted Source Evaluations used to improve source reliability ratings. Researched individual statements provided in the Initial Intelligence Reports (IIR) to produce evaluations used to determine source veracity and reliability. Published Source Evaluations into CIDNE. Imported data into the Production Review/Source Validation Review (PR/SVR) format to be submitted to Division for review and implementation. Produced the daily HUMINT Summary (HUMSUM) summarizing the daily IIRs and providing precise assessments. Conducted HUMINT related data pulls and research to support other cells such as targeting, fusion, and Intelligence, Surveillance and Reconnaissance (ISR). Provided the main source of continuity for the HAC throughout the Relief in Place/Transfer of Authority (RIP/TOA) process from the 116th BCT to the 3-2nd BCT. Upon completion of TOA, assumed the position of HAC Lead and undertook responsibilities of training new analysts regarding the Source Evaluation Process, HUMSUM and other HAC related products. Also conducted Quality Control/Quality Assurance (QC/QA) of evaluations and products, maintained scheduling for maximum performance and allocation of projects and duties.

title: Geospatial Exploitation Office Watch Analyst (SIGINT)
description: Analyzed and summarized critical intelligence data in support of tactical operations, disseminating 50+ SIGINT reports daily. Deployed to Bagram, Afghanistan to provide in-depth geospatial metadata analysis supporting High Value Target (HVT) and Medium Value Target (MVT) missions for both U.S. and second party Special Operations Forces (SOF) operations. Working knowledge of ArcGIS, NSANet and various databases such as Mainway, Banyan, Cultweave and Broomstick to process and disseminate intelligence information. Used ArcView to create shape files in support of force protection and situation awareness activities. Advised DoD civilian and military supervisors regarding quality control, personnel training and upgrades. Maintained and supported $70K workstation.

title: Intel Operations Analyst/Trainer
description: Developed Common Operational Pictures (COP) while fusing SIGINT and HUMINT metadata, utilizing ARGIS, Google-Earth, Falcon-View and other GEO-spatial tools in order to display both Regional or Theater operations status. Produced analytic methodologies to accomplish data mining, data fusion and geo-profiling. Instructed PALANTIR, Analyst Notebook, ArcGIS 10.1, IC-reach, Tripwire Analytic Capability, and Distributed Common Ground System-Army (DCGS-A). Supported and trained SOF Operator (18F) and SOF Intelligence collectors (35P/35N) with developing Tactics, Techniques and Procedure (TTP) to combat Counter-Terrorism (CT) activities in OIF/OND and OEF Theaters using COIC, NSA, DIA, and DCSG software. Provided analytical reach-back support to forward deployed analysts, including training support and integration. Conducted Mobile Training at USASOC, MARSOC, EUCOM, PACOM, and CENTCOM to mentor military analyst and collection specialist on massing and fusing data on multiple networks to include CENTRIX, BICES, SIPR, and JWICS in efforts to increase exploitation on insurgent networks.

title: Collections Manager
description: Responsible for managing collection plans, organizing strategies, coordinating systems and evaluating requirements to integrate precision collection for collaboration with national-level decision makers. Monitoring un-evaluated traffic as it is received by the ONEROOF server resident on NSANet, and manipulated it as required to ensure proper processing. Produce descriptive intelligence assessments in support of Priority Intelligence Requirements (PIRs) based on information obtained from Real Time Regional Gateway (RTRG). Utilized Glaive system to maintain collection efforts by allocating receivers and operators across the region and around the world to maintain continuity on potential threats. Updated Caroline and Surrey database to maintain and monitor collection requirement. Integrated teams of collection specialists preparing articulated and systematic focused intelligence to exploit the capabilities of the national, theater, and tactical collection systems. Provided direct support to customer in driving complex worldwide operations to develop actionable intelligence against the highest priority threats to National Security. Developed a substantive expertise with identifying customers, functional missions, strategic focus, terrorism, and weapon proliferation.

title: SIGINT Collection Team Lead (SOT-A / LLVI)
description: Deployed to Afghanistan in support of the Joint Special Operations Command. Served as liaison to Joint Interagency Task Force to development collection plans and gathered data on threat networks. Exported collection data into SIGINT database to be utilized by IC-Reach, Cultweave, and other SIGINT databases to develop effective targeting efforts and exploit threat networks. Conducted tactical Signals Intelligence (SIGINT) collection operations using military low-level voice intercept (LLVI) equipment to include, DRT 1301C, DARBE, Wolfhound, AN/PRD-13, and AR8200/IC-R20. Conducted over a 100 combat missions into various regions of Afghanistan, validating various National and Tactical Requirements supporting coalition operations and analysis and targeting terrorist networks. Tracked and identified High Value targets of interest unitizing advance equipment such the Digital Receiver Technology DRT 1501, DAMEON, GSK, AN/PRD-13/14, Gossamer and Stingray systems. Maintained and communicated with command and other teams on digital and HF radios including; PRC-117, PSC-5, PRC-148, RT-1523, and PRC-119 radios.

summary: Mr. Allen, a former U.S. Army Chief Warrant Officer Four, is a Senior Signals Intelligence Analyst and Manager with over 28 years of successful leadership, managerial, product reporting and analytical experience at tactical, joint, combined and multi-national levels in positions of increasing responsibility including two military deployments to Iraq and one civilian deployment to Afghanistan. Over 25 years active duty service in the U.S. Army and nearly four years as an Army Contract working in senior positions. Experienced in Corps and below intelligence and information operations, including the planning, collection, analysis and distribution of critical information during combat, peace keeping and force protection operations. Mr. Allen also has extensive experience developing architecture with IT solutions and leveraging intelligence disciplines to support military operations/decisions during combat, peace keeping, and force protection missions. Mr. Allen also possesses extensive experience in leading and managing diverse teams, has excellent writing and interpersonal skills, solid analytical and critical thinking skills and strong product reporting/editing skills with experience in Signals Analysis, MASINT, IMINT and Geospatial Metadata Analysis. Mr. Allen is adept at collecting, reviewing, and disseminating intelligence information and providing accurate intelligence products to senior officials and intelligence organizations. Finally, Mr. Allen is a proven analyst, technician, trainer and leader and has always produced exemplary results with 100% mission success.

title: Ground SIGINT Specialist
description: Identifies, researches, and reports target intelligence data in accordance with operational guidance in support of Task Force Operations; provided real-time critical intelligence and threat warning to allied forces saving countless lives Daily utilizes Association, ContraOctave, Dishfire, Homebase, Mainway, Banyan, Cultweave, RTRG, Sortinglead, Taperlay, and Voicemaster to provide near real time analysis and reporting Supports analysis and development of intelligence products; applied traffic analysis techniques to raw data and writes technical, time-sensitive product reports based on national-level intelligence requirements. Coordinates with intelligence analysts throughout the theater of operations to steer reporting efforts and better respond to emerging consumer requirements Trains/mentors junior analysts on various analysis and reporting tools to include of UIS, JCMT, ONEROOF, Center Mass, Gist Queue Monitors UIS to retrieve SRI data in preparation for drafting time-sensitive reports Provides real-time SIGINT support to Multinational Forces and Combat Search and Rescue operations across Afghanistan utilizing RTRG tools and OneRoof, Nucleon, Dishfire and Pinwale database queries Utilizes the following tools to author, compile, retrieve, and send intelligence reports: CPE, Anchory/MAUI , Centermass, Gistgueue, UIS, One Roof, Intelink, and ArcGis; produced over 50 reports per day Provides Collection Management using Joint Collection Management Tools (JCMT) to operational forces Lead analyst on several high profile sensitive reporting efforts Liaises with intelligence community partners on Counter-Insurgency techniques, tactics and procedures, coordinated intelligence sharing with NSA Research Directorate Conducts independent research to write reports to satisfy published customer intelligence requirements Performs social network analysis in Analyst Notebook on Afghanistan threat networks

title: Warrant Officer SIGINT Technician
description: Served as Director and Senior Military Intelligence Analyst; supervised and provided operational analytical support and training for more than 200 Soldiers, 50 DA Civilians and 30 Contractors. Served as the senior advisor to executive level leaders with the responsibility of solving the unit’s Warrant Officer Utilization problems; individually conducted a study and prepared a strategy which allowed senior leaders to effectively utilize Warrant Officers within the organization. Provided input to the staff during the annual review and revision of the units authorization documents (TDAs, MTOEs) based on mission assignments, organizational restructuring and/or higher headquarters directed administrative changes, manpower or equipment surveys, new equipment developments or higher headquarters directed changes. Maintained accountability of sensitive equipment valued at $60 million by conducting monthly physical inventory of non-expendable property and equipment during combat operations. Coordinated and organized the training for more than 1000 Soldiers, DA civilians and contractor on the Equal Opportunity and Equal Employment Opportunity Program. Managed numerous budgets between $85,000.00 and $2.2 million; participated as budget representative to higher echelon in regards to special studies, projects, and meetings. Participated in weekly organizational staff management meetings providing input and representation on contract management, information technology, resource allocation, equipment procurement and incoming and outgoing task/requirements management. Supervised the processing, analysis, reporting, utilization of specialized software and techniques in support of multiple military organizations requirements. Responsible for the planning, directing, coordinating, implementation and evaluation of technical policy and procedures for the sections daily operations.

title: Writer, Broadcaster and Sports Journalist
description: Writer at acclaimed Raider Fan Website along with Sports Journalist/Broadcaster at the Armed Forces Network (AFN) under pseudonym "Captain Jack Rack'Em." His articles for Raider Nation Times come under his byline in his 'Walk The Plank' section, and during football season he is the creator and lead co-host of the AFN Radio GTMO "Pure Pigskin Football Show" - a weekly two hour College/Pro Football overview and prognostication show running from pre-season until Super Bowl Saturday the day before the ultimate contest, "Pure Pigskin" features listener interaction via call-ins on views and trivia questions, as well as in studio featured guests. "Captain Jack" additionally is the 'Play by Play Announcer' for the Guantanamo Men's/Women's Army VS Navy Flag-Football Game.

title: Senior Counter-Terrorism/Counter-Intelligence/Personnel Recovery Analyst / SME
description: - Senior Analyst within the Personnel Recovery (PR) Division at USCENTCOM, serving as the historical case-analyst for previous Iraq-theater PR Cases, as well as the Subject-matter-expert (SME) for current PR cases within the Afghanistan-Pakistan (AFPAK) Theater. - USCENTCOM representative at the semi-annual PR conference in Qatar in May 2011, along with the FBI sponsored three-day event detailing debriefs and IC-case presentation of former UK hostage Peter Moore in the National Capital Region. Completed notes and disseminated to members of the IC to include FBI, DIA, PRD/J-33 in Baghdad, Iraq, and the IJC in Afghanistan. - Analyzes all-source intelligence information regarding current and historic cases involving USCENTCOM and or other designated Persons of Interest (POI) with designated PR numbers in order to resolve the cases to their ultimate conclusion via recovery (live or otherwise); handles daily RFIs on PR cases as well as several ‘monitoring’ events of Western hijack victims in the CENTCOM theater. - Works to refine/update collections efforts with the CENTCOM Collection Management Office to include directing and producing HUMINT SDRs/IIR Evaluations as well as Imagery tasking. - Responsible for the production of two JICCENT Intelligence Highlights (JIH)s, seventeen Commander’s Daily Updates (CDU)s detailing historic PR cases as well as current developments in ongoing cases in the AF-PAK theater of operations, and several ad-hoc PR-specific Commander’s Executive Intelligence Highlights (CEIH)s / Summary Intelligence Reports (SIR)s. - Graduated Personnel Recovery Execution (300), Plans & Operations (301); Nonconventional Assisted Recovery (303); Reintegration (296); Debriefing (297) courses. - Attends at least two-three weekly meetings/VTCs for the ongoing PR cases; attends weekly PR planning meetings/ phone coordination with deployed PR analyst to IJC Kabul. - Conducts liaison between the IC / COCOMS in PR-related enterprises.

title: Senior Counter-Terrorism/Counter-Intelligence Analyst & Training Coordinator
description: - Senior Counter-Terrorism / Counter-Intelligence analyst in the USCENTCOM J-2X-JAT-“Inspired Nomad” (IN) Division. Additionally, requested by name for USCENTCOM J2 directed Crisis Action Team (CAT) dealing with HAMAS Resupply. Conducted daily analysis and intelligence data-mining of Iranian intelligence and related functionalities, using IC-Reach, CULTWEAVE, and Google Earth. - Received the National Intelligence Medallion, presented by the Director of National Intelligence for work within IN Division (Jan – Dec 2008). Received personal ‘Kudos’ from US Ambassador Crocker and the Baghdad C/O, the USCENTCOM J2, and USCENTJIC Commander for requested intelligence products dealing with areas of his expertise within both the IN Division / HAMAS Resupply CAT. - Produced dynamic and detailed intelligence to include two comprehensive JICCENT SPECIAL REPORTS (JSRs), along with over 250 Joint Intelligence Highlights (JIHs) / Summary Intelligence Reports (SIRs) briefed to Commander, U.S. Central Command and the National Intelligence Community (IC). Produced Desk Note/Overviews, 420+ PowerPoint graphics, and fifteen Biographic Summary intelligence products directly for consumption by USCENTCOM J2, CENTCOM deployed assets, and National Intelligence Community. - Conducted detailed training for IN Division on Iranian intelligence with accompanying graphics for consumption by the IC of delineated targets by J2-X division. - Acknowledged and recognized Subject Matter Expert (SME) and Training Expert dealing with specific facets of Iranian intelligence and HAMAS issues. - Conducts near daily coordination, training, and analysis with the entire spectrum of IC agencies to include the CIA, NSA, DIA, Theater Commands, deployed USCENTCOM Staff/HQ elements, State Dept, Treasury Dept, USEMBASSY Baghdad, National Ground Intelligence Center and other intelligence entities eliciting and soliciting products and information.

title: Counter-Terrorism/Intelligence Analyst / Training Coordinator / Tomahawk Targeteer
description: Counter-Terrorism/Intelligence Analyst and Training Coordinator – USSOCOM MacDill AFB, FL Apr03 – Dec06 - Senior Counter-Terrorism Intelligence (CT/I) analyst and training coordinator within the Intelligence-Operations Fusion, and Psychological Operations Divisions. - Cited for his efforts within the SOCOM Center for Special Operations (SCSO) Operational Planning Division, as his contributions directly impacted how the intelligence community views CT/I information at the National level. - USSOCOM Navy Element Training Coordinator, responsible for in-rate training requirements, General Military Training (GMT) requirements for Navy personnel, and the ordering of classified publications for training guides, pamphlets, and other training resources. Facilitated several training evolutions for both Navy and other service personnel. - Knowledge of Special Operations and Intelligence directly affected his division’s ability to complete its planning missions through its expansion, relocation and maturation within the SCSO - Senior intelligence advisor and manager of three divisions within the SCSO during his tour, responsible for up to seventy military and civilian intelligence personnel. CT/I analyst for the US Central Command (CENTCOM) and US Pacific Command (PACOM) area of responsibility (AOR) regional working groups Tomahawk Systems Imagery Targeting Analyst/Training– USJFCOM Cruise Missile Support Activity Norfolk, VA Jun02 – Mar03 - Digital Imagery Workstation (DIWS) targets developed, incorporated, and expedited for Tomahawk launches against Iraqi facilities as part of OPERATION IRAQI FREEDOM - Graduated 10-week Navy/Marine Intelligence Training Center DIWS course mastering intricacies of target aim-point data and digital imagery data production, - Gained certifications from Cruise Missile Support Activity (CMSA) Atlantic as DIWS Analyst; Senior DIWS Analyst; TOMAHAWK Land Attack Missile (TLAM) Precision Targeting Workstation (PTW) Analyst,

title: Writer, Broadcaster and Sports Journalist
description: Writer at acclaimed Raider Fan Website along with Sports Journalist/Broadcaster at the Armed Forces Network (AFN) under pseudonym "Captain Jack Rack'Em." His articles for Raider Nation Times come under his byline in his 'Walk The Plank' section, and during football season he is the creator and lead co-host of the AFN Radio GTMO "Pure Pigskin Football Show" - a weekly two hour College/Pro Football overview and prognostication show running from pre-season until Super Bowl Saturday the day before the ultimate contest, "Pure Pigskin" features listener interaction via call-ins on views and trivia questions, as well as in studio featured guests. "Captain Jack" additionally is the 'Play by Play Announcer' for the Guantanamo Men's/Women's Army VS Navy Flag-Football Game.

title: Senior Counter-Terrorism/Counter-Intelligence/Personnel Recovery Analyst / SME
description: - Senior Analyst within the Personnel Recovery (PR) Division at USCENTCOM, serving as the historical case-analyst for previous Iraq-theater PR Cases, as well as the Subject-matter-expert (SME) for current PR cases within the Afghanistan-Pakistan (AFPAK) Theater. - USCENTCOM representative at the semi-annual PR conference in Qatar in May 2011, along with the FBI sponsored three-day event detailing debriefs and IC-case presentation of former UK hostage Peter Moore in the National Capital Region. Completed notes and disseminated to members of the IC to include FBI, DIA, PRD/J-33 in Baghdad, Iraq, and the IJC in Afghanistan. - Analyzes all-source intelligence information regarding current and historic cases involving USCENTCOM and or other designated Persons of Interest (POI) with designated PR numbers in order to resolve the cases to their ultimate conclusion via recovery (live or otherwise); handles daily RFIs on PR cases as well as several ‘monitoring’ events of Western hijack victims in the CENTCOM theater. - Works to refine/update collections efforts with the CENTCOM Collection Management Office to include directing and producing HUMINT SDRs/IIR Evaluations as well as Imagery tasking. - Responsible for the production of two JICCENT Intelligence Highlights (JIH)s, seventeen Commander’s Daily Updates (CDU)s detailing historic PR cases as well as current developments in ongoing cases in the AF-PAK theater of operations, and several ad-hoc PR-specific Commander’s Executive Intelligence Highlights (CEIH)s / Summary Intelligence Reports (SIR)s. - Graduated Personnel Recovery Execution (300), Plans & Operations (301); Nonconventional Assisted Recovery (303); Reintegration (296); Debriefing (297) courses. - Attends at least two-three weekly meetings/VTCs for the ongoing PR cases; attends weekly PR planning meetings/ phone coordination with deployed PR analyst to IJC Kabul. - Conducts liaison between the IC / COCOMS in PR-related enterprises.

title: Senior Counter-Terrorism/Counter-Intelligence Analyst & Training Coordinator
description: - Senior Counter-Terrorism / Counter-Intelligence analyst in the USCENTCOM J-2X-JAT-“Inspired Nomad” (IN) Division. Additionally, requested by name for USCENTCOM J2 directed Crisis Action Team (CAT) dealing with HAMAS Resupply. Conducted daily analysis and intelligence data-mining of Iranian intelligence and related functionalities, using IC-Reach, CULTWEAVE, and Google Earth. - Received the National Intelligence Medallion, presented by the Director of National Intelligence for work within IN Division (Jan – Dec 2008). Received personal ‘Kudos’ from US Ambassador Crocker and the Baghdad C/O, the USCENTCOM J2, and USCENTJIC Commander for requested intelligence products dealing with areas of his expertise within both the IN Division / HAMAS Resupply CAT. - Produced dynamic and detailed intelligence to include two comprehensive JICCENT SPECIAL REPORTS (JSRs), along with over 250 Joint Intelligence Highlights (JIHs) / Summary Intelligence Reports (SIRs) briefed to Commander, U.S. Central Command and the National Intelligence Community (IC). Produced Desk Note/Overviews, 420+ PowerPoint graphics, and fifteen Biographic Summary intelligence products directly for consumption by USCENTCOM J2, CENTCOM deployed assets, and National Intelligence Community. - Conducted detailed training for IN Division on Iranian intelligence with accompanying graphics for consumption by the IC of delineated targets by J2-X division. - Acknowledged and recognized Subject Matter Expert (SME) and Training Expert dealing with specific facets of Iranian intelligence and HAMAS issues. - Conducts near daily coordination, training, and analysis with the entire spectrum of IC agencies to include the CIA, NSA, DIA, Theater Commands, deployed USCENTCOM Staff/HQ elements, State Dept, Treasury Dept, USEMBASSY Baghdad, National Ground Intelligence Center and other intelligence entities eliciting and soliciting products and information.

title: Counter-Terrorism/Intelligence Analyst / Training Coordinator / Tomahawk Targeteer
description: Counter-Terrorism/Intelligence Analyst and Training Coordinator – USSOCOM MacDill AFB, FL Apr03 – Dec06 - Senior Counter-Terrorism Intelligence (CT/I) analyst and training coordinator within the Intelligence-Operations Fusion, and Psychological Operations Divisions. - Cited for his efforts within the SOCOM Center for Special Operations (SCSO) Operational Planning Division, as his contributions directly impacted how the intelligence community views CT/I information at the National level. - USSOCOM Navy Element Training Coordinator, responsible for in-rate training requirements, General Military Training (GMT) requirements for Navy personnel, and the ordering of classified publications for training guides, pamphlets, and other training resources. Facilitated several training evolutions for both Navy and other service personnel. - Knowledge of Special Operations and Intelligence directly affected his division’s ability to complete its planning missions through its expansion, relocation and maturation within the SCSO - Senior intelligence advisor and manager of three divisions within the SCSO during his tour, responsible for up to seventy military and civilian intelligence personnel. CT/I analyst for the US Central Command (CENTCOM) and US Pacific Command (PACOM) area of responsibility (AOR) regional working groups Tomahawk Systems Imagery Targeting Analyst/Training– USJFCOM Cruise Missile Support Activity Norfolk, VA Jun02 – Mar03 - Digital Imagery Workstation (DIWS) targets developed, incorporated, and expedited for Tomahawk launches against Iraqi facilities as part of OPERATION IRAQI FREEDOM - Graduated 10-week Navy/Marine Intelligence Training Center DIWS course mastering intricacies of target aim-point data and digital imagery data production, - Gained certifications from Cruise Missile Support Activity (CMSA) Atlantic as DIWS Analyst; Senior DIWS Analyst; TOMAHAWK Land Attack Missile (TLAM) Precision Targeting Workstation (PTW) Analyst,
